 <subsection xml:id="subsec-proportion-problemsolving">
  <title>Solving Problems Involving Rates and Ratios</title>
    <p>
      There are many real-life problems in which proportional reasoning can be applied. Some examples from various contexts follow.
    </p>
    
   

  
    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          You are making many pizzas for a large party. Your favorite recipe makes 20 ounces of dough, which is the right amount for two 12-inch diameter pizzas. You plan to make six 16-inch pizzas for the party. By what factor should you multiply or scale the recipe, and how many ounces of dough will that make?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
       <p>
        Assume that the thickness of a 16-inch pizza is the same as the thickness of a 12-inch pizza. You can compare the total area of pizza made from one recipe with the total area of pizza you plan to make for the party. 
        </p>
        <p>
        The formula for the area of a circle of radius <m>r</m> is <m>A=\pi r^{2}</m>. Recall that the radius of a circle is half of its diameter, so the original recipe makes two 6-inch radius pizzas and you want to make six 8-inch radius pizzas. Those areas are as follows:
        </p>
        <sidebyside>
          <stack>
          <p>
            Original Recipe: Two pies of radius 6 inches
          </p>
          <p>
            <me>
              A=\pi (6)^{2}\cdot2=72 \pi \text{ square inches}
            </me>
          </p>
          </stack>
          <stack>
          <p>
            For Party: Six pies of radius 8 inches
            <me>
              A=\pi (8)^{2}\cdot 6=384 \pi \text{ square inches}
            </me>
            
          </p>
          </stack>
        </sidebyside>
        <p>
          The ratio of the area of pizza needed for the party to the area of pizza made by one recipe is <m>\frac{384\pi}{72\pi}=\frac{16}{3}\approx 5.33</m>
        </p>
        <p>
          When we make the dough, we will multiply the amount of each ingredient by <m>\frac{16}{3}</m>, which is the factor you should use to scale up the recipe.
        </p>
        <p>
          The resulting amount of dough should be <m>20\cdot\frac{16}{3}\approx106.67</m> ounces. For context, that is 6.67 pounds of dough. You will need a very large bowl!
        </p>

      </solution>
    </example>
